## Architecture Rules

### Constants — gameConfig.ts is the only place for numbers
Every tunable number lives in `src/constants/gameConfig.ts`.
HP values, damage values, speed values, cooldown timers, radii, position coordinates, energy thresholds — all of them.
If you write a raw number into game logic, stop. Name the constant. Add it to gameConfig. Import it.

```typescript
// Correct — import and use named constants
import { HEROES, ENEMIES, COMBAT, FORMATION, WARDEN } from '../constants/gameConfig';
hero.currentHP = HEROES.KAEL.BASE_HP;

// Wrong — magic numbers in logic files
hero.currentHP = 1800;
```

### Interfaces — types/index.ts is the only place for types
All TypeScript interfaces and type aliases live in `src/types/index.ts`.
Never define interfaces inline in scene files, entity files, or system files.

### File Length
Maximum 300 lines per file where practical.
If a file is approaching this limit, split it into a focused sub-module.
`BattleScene.ts` does not contain targeting logic. `AutoBattleSystem.ts` does not contain wave spawning.

### One Responsibility Per File
- `AutoBattleSystem.ts` — combat loop and attack resolution only
- `TargetingSystem.ts` — target selection only
- `FormationSystem.ts` — position assignment and walk-in only
- `UltimateSystem.ts` — energy and ultimate resolution only
- `WaveSystem.ts` — wave spawning and boss behavior only
- `SaveSystem.ts` — localStorage read/write only

### Scene Cleanup
Every Phaser scene implements `shutdown()`.
`shutdown()` destroys every Phaser.GameObjects object, Graphics object, Tween, Timer, and event listener created in `create()`.
A scene that leaks on transition will crash the app after a few session loops.

### TypeScript Strictness
- TypeScript only. No `.js` files in `src/`.
- Never use `any`. Define an interface.
- Use `as const` on all config objects in `gameConfig.ts`.

### Standard Formulas (copy these exactly)

```typescript
// LERP movement — delta in seconds
const dx = target.x - unit.x;
const dy = target.y - unit.y;
const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy);
if (dist > unit.speed * delta) {
  unit.x += (dx / dist) * unit.speed * delta;
  unit.y += (dy / dist) * unit.speed * delta;
} else {
  unit.x = target.x;
  unit.y = target.y;
}

// Circle collision — avoid sqrt for performance
function overlaps(a: { x: number; y: number; radius: number },
                  b: { x: number; y: number; radius: number }): boolean {
  const dx = a.x - b.x;
  const dy = a.y - b.y;
  return dx * dx + dy * dy < (a.radius + b.radius) * (a.radius + b.radius);
}

// Damage formula
const finalDamage = Math.max(COMBAT.MIN_DAMAGE, attacker.attack - defender.defense);
```

